Regarding my Robolectric conundrum here is my dilemma.

I have this class which maps a `FilterEntity` to `ContentValues` for inserting to a database.

```
public class FilterEntityToContentValuesMapper implements Mapper&lt;FilterEntity, ContentValues&gt; {

    @Override
    public ContentValues mapOrThrow(FilterEntity filter) throws MappingException {
        final ContentValues values = new ContentValues();

        values.put(FilterSchema.COLUMN_ID, filter.id().toString());
        values.put(FilterSchema.COLUMN_NAME, filter.name());
        // and others...

        return values;
    }
}
```

I of course want to unit test this class but the problem is with `ContentValues`. `ContentValues#put` will throw a not-mocked exception from Android and I can't mock it with PowerMock since I am instantiating inside the method. I see two options here:

The first option is to make a `ContentValuesFactory` with a `newInstance()` method which will be mocked with PowerMock (`ContentValues` is final) and return a mocked `ContentValues`. This would change the code like so:

```
public class FilterEntityToContentValuesMapper implements Mapper&lt;FilterEntity, ContentValues&gt; {

    private final ContentValuesValuesFactory contentValuesFactory;

    public FilterEntityToContentValuesMapper(ContentValuesValuesFactory contentValuesFactory) {
        this.contentValuesFactory = contentValuesFactory;
    }

    @Override
    public ContentValues mapOrThrow(SearchFilterEntity filter) throws MappingException {
        final ContentValues values = contentValuesFactory.newInstance();
		// everything else is the same
    }
}
```

The con here is that I really don't want to make a factory in an Android app especially since this is an issue with the Android SDK being barely testable.

The second option would be to use Robolectric and call it a day. The con here is that I don't trust Robolectric and I avoid it as much as possible.

What are your opinions?

